An '''oak-heath forest''' is a [[plant community]] association and type of [[forest]] [[ecology]]. It is a [[deciduous forest]] type of well-drained, [[acid]]ic soils, characterized by oaks (''[[Quercus]]'') and plants of the heath family, [[Ericaceae]].<ref>{{cite web|page=8|url=http://www.crmc.ri.gov/coastallandscapes/Coastal_Buffer_Planting_Guide.pdf|title=Coastal Buffer Zone Planting Guide| date=August 2008|publisher=Rhode Island Coastal Resources Management Council|accessdate=2011-02-27}}</ref> It is commonly found in the high elevations of the eastern United States. {{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} Such forest areas typically have a dense fibrous [[root layer]] at the surface of the soil, and in many areas predominate on south-facing or southwest-facing slopes.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} Many of the existing oak-heath forests once featured [[American chestnut]] as an important canopy species.<ref name=VDCR>[http://www.dcr.virginia.gov/natural_heritage/ncTIIIe.shtml ''The Natural Communities of Virginia Classification of Ecological Community Groups'' (Version 2.3), Virginia Department of Conservation and Recreation, 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115181617/http://www.dcr.virginia.gov/natural_heritage/ncTIIIe.shtml |date=January 15, 2009 }}</ref>
==Oaks== Oaks (''[[Quercus]]'') characteristic of an oak-heath associations include white oak, ''[[Quercus alba]]''; black oak, ''[[Quercus velutina]]''; scarlet oak, ''[[Quercus coccinea]]''; chestnut oak, ''[[Quercus prinus]]'', and red oak, ''[[Quercus rubra]]''.<ref name=VDCR/><ref name=NCNHP>Schafale, M. P. and A. S. Weakley. 1990. ''Classification of the natural communities of North Carolina: third approximation''. North Carolina Natural Heritage Program, North Carolina Division of Parks and Recreation.</ref>
==Heaths== [[Heath]] plants common to this ecology include mountain-laurel, ''[[Kalmia latifolia]]'', various blueberries, genus ''[[Vaccinium]]'', huckleberries, genus ''[[Gaylussacia]]'', sourwood (or sorrel-tree), ''[[Oxydendron arboreum]]'', and azaleas and rhododendrons, genus ''[[Rhododendron]]''. These are all usually shrubs, except for ''Oxydendron'', which is usually a small tree. There are also heaths that are sub-shrubs, usually trailing on the ground, including teaberry, ''[[Gaultheria procumbens]]'' and trailing arbutus, ''[[Epigaea repens]]''.<ref name=VDCR/><ref name=NCNHP/>
