An '''optical solar reflector''' ('''OSR''') consists of a top layer made out of [[quartz]], over a [[Reflection (optics)|reflecting]] layer made of [[metal]].

OSRs are used for [[radiators]] on [[spacecraft]]. The quartz outer layer lets the [[Sun|solar]] light through which reflects on the metal layer. This results in a low [[absorption coefficient]]. The quartz layer is a good [[Infrared|IR]] emitter.  The result of these properties is a good emitting, low absorbing material, thus making it a [[cold material]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wertz|first1=James R.|last2=Larson|first2=Wiley J.|title=Space Mission Analysis and Design|date=1991|publisher=Kluwer Academic|location=Dordrecht|isbn=0-7923-0970-7|pages=380–381|edition=2. print}}</ref>

Optical solar reflectors are a type of [[First surface mirror|second surface mirror]].

